	<string>public.app-category.utilities</string>
	<key>LSMinimumSystemVersion</key>
	<string>${MACOSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET}</string>
	<key>NSAppleScriptEnabled</key>
	<string>YES</string>
	<key>NSBluetoothAlwaysUsageDescription</key>
	<string>KisMac uses Bluetooth to passively scan for nearby Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) devices for authorized security auditing: it inventories advertised names, service UUIDs, manufacturer data, and signal strength, and — only for a device you explicitly select — enumerates its GATT services. KisMac never auto-connects and all data stays on your Mac.</string>
	<key>NSLocationWhenInUseUsageDescription</key>
	<string>KisMac needs your location because modern macOS only reveals Wi-Fi network names (SSID) and access-point hardware addresses (BSSID) to apps that are authorized for Location. Without it, Wi-Fi recon results are hidden or redacted. Your location is used only to unlock this Wi-Fi scan data; it is not transmitted off your Mac.</string>
	<key>NSMainNibFile</key>
	<string>MainMenu</string>
	<key>NSPrincipalClass</key>
	<string>NSApplication</string>
